<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-07-30T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-07-30T04:00:00-05:00" n="608" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d608">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113 Airplanes/1: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-07-30T17:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 30,
                                        1926—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received July 30—10
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>309. My telegram 162, April 3, 2 p.m. I am reliably informed that the
                            British Government has recently removed commercial aeroplanes from the
                            list of articles procured under the arms embargo and that Avro machines
                            are now being offered for sale in China by representatives of British
                            interests.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>